  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">UNIDO-CFDAIED Centers of Excellence in China</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Food safety and drug supervision is a global issue. The significance of China in global food safety and drug supervision is rising and presenting to be unique and irreplaceable. The establishment of pool of professional food and drug inspectors is recognized as one of China&#x2019;s strategic working priorities on food and drug safety. Food inspection is targeted in the &#x201C;Healthy China 2030 Strategic Plan&#x201D; and the 13th Five-Year National Plan on Food Safety, among which the latter requests to clarify and standardize the qualification, duty, training, management and evaluation for professional food inspectors, through strengthening training bases at the provincial level for inspectors and promoting online training platforms. Regulators are required to have at least 40 study hours per year for professional trainings, while entry level staff ought to have at least 90 hours every year.

Food safety is also top-highlighted on the agenda of the cooperation between UNIDO and the former China Food and Drug Administration (CFDA). Both the &#x201C;UNIDO-China Strategic Cooperation Framework 2018 &#x2013; 2021&#x201D; and the &#x201C;UNIDO Country Programme for China 2016-2020&#x201D; signed between the Ministry of Commerce of China and UNIDO recognize food safety as one of the emphases of the UNIDO-China cooperation. The Memorandum of Understanding signed between the former CFDA and UNIDO in June 2015 proved its significance in facilitating the cooperation between the both parties in the area of food safety and drug safety. UNIDO presents its accumulated wide experience and expertise in the area of food value chain investment, quality control, compliance to international standardization and capacity building, which is strengthened as well in the close and proactive interaction with other relevant international organizations and institutionalizations, and facilitates to introduce the advanced international experience and best practice in the food safety area of China. For instance, UNIDO&#x2019;s portfolio and connection lies within the Global Consumer Goods Forum (CGF) in the collaboration with the Global Food Safety Initiative (GFSI). UNIDO is also part of the World Bank leadership group of the Global Food Safety Partnership (GFSP) as a unique public-private initiative aiming at combining food safety training and technical support so developing countries can improve their food safety systems and benefit from better compliance with food safety standards.

The initiative of the Centres of Excellence (CoE) is therefore motivated to establish a harmonized competency-based food and drug safety training system across China in line with related international knowledge and practice and to international recognition at the central level, therefore to guide and support harmonized competency-based training at the local level and to achieve the goal of improving the overall food safety and drug supervision capacity building in China. Moreover, in the maturity of timing the proposal could be also considered as serving the South-South Cooperation and the Belt and Road Initiative.

It is agreed to strengthen the intervention of UNIDO in China&#x2019;s food safety and drug supervision in the aspects of training qualification package, trainers, training quality management system and international training through profiling, benchmarking and capacity building etc. against best international practices and experience in food safety and drug supervision. UNIDO will serve for the overall capacity development framework of CFDAIED, and help to design and provide technical and institutional support in food sector. The CFDAIED will take this as a reference to design drug related content in the CoE system with possible support from UNIDO. This is in line with and highlights UNIDO&#x2019;s core functions lying in technical cooperation, policy analysis and advice, norms and standards, and convening and partnerships, to target knowledge transfer and strengthen institutions, as confirmed in UNIDO Medium-term Programme Framework, 2018-2021, towards achieving SDGs...</narrative>
  </description>
